<div>		



<span class="section_title">Allied Associations Bring Full Spectrum Of Consumer Electronics To The 2005 International CES</span>

	<br><br>
	<span class="subhead">More than 60 International and US-Based Participants Underscore Diversity of International CES </span>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>Arlington, Virginia&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/22/2004</i></strong>
<br><br>
From broadcasters to government electronics and beyond, the Allied Association program at the 2005 International CES brings together a record 64 organizations from the full spectrum of the consumer technology industry.  The 2005 International CES, the world's largest annual tradeshow for consumer technology, will take place January 6-9 in Las Vegas, Nevada.
<p>
"The Allied Association program at the International CES allows us to extend a special recognition and courtesy to the numerous organizations that contribute to the consumer electronics industry in a capacity beyond the traditional manufacturer, dealer or retailer," said Gary Shapiro, president and CEO of the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA), the producer of CES.  "This year we are honored to have participants from all over the world, including representatives from Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, Japan, Lithuania, Malaysia, Philippines and Taiwan."
<p>
Organizations signing on to the International CES' Allied Association program will have a presence at CES and access to the Allied Association Lounge with a business center, meeting rooms and other VIP opportunities. 
US-based Allied Associations:
<p>
* 1394 Trade Association<br>
* American Hardware Manufacturers Association<br>
* American Society of Association Executives<br>
* Association of Public Television Stations<br>
* Broadband Service Providers Association<br>
* CEDIA<br>
* CEEA<br>
* Computer & Communications Industry Association<br>
* Computer Systems Policy Project<br>
